      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, no matter how far apart they are. It's like having two magical, invisible strings connecting two distant, mischievous goblins. If one goblin starts dancing, the other goblin will start dancing too, even if they're in different parts of the forest. This is different from classical correlation, where objects might be connected in some way, but they don't have that instant, spooky connection. Think of it like two regular goblins who just happen to have similar tastes in snacks; they might eat the same kind of fruit, but there's no magical link between them. In quantum entanglement, it's as if the goblins are connected by an invisible, magical string that makes them dance together, no matter how far apart they are.",
      "source": "target",
